Accessing a Web Feature Service with Python¶

This notebook demonstrates how to programmatically access an OGC Web Feature Service from the National Environmental Information Infrastructure using Python. In this example the service endpoint is known but if it wasn't it could be found from the catalogue (see Accessing the Catalogue example).

To access the WFS service we can use the OWSLib Python library.

First we need to import the WebFeatureService class

In [2]:
from owslib.wfs import WebFeatureService

Now we can instantiate an OWSLib object that connects to the Web Feature Service, and check the title and abstract of the service.

In [4]:
wfs=WebFeatureService('http://www.environment.gov.au/mapping/services/ogc_services/World_Heritage_Areas_label/MapServer/WFSServer')

Here is a simple request to get some of the features. To minimise the size of the request a maximum of 10 is requested.

In [16]:
features = wfs.getfeature(typename=['ogc_services_World_Heritage_Areas_label:World_Heritage_Areas_Australia_label'], maxfeatures=10, propertyname=None)
In [17]:
wfs_response=features.read()
In [ ]:
By examining the first few characters of the response it can be seen that the data has come back as a WFS FeatureCollection in XML format.
In [23]:
wfs_response[:200]
Out[23]:
b"<wfs:FeatureCollection xsi:schemaLocation='http://www.environment.gov.au/mapping/services/ogc_services//World_Heritage_Areas_label/MapServer/WFSServer http://www.environment.gov.au/mapping/services/og"

To decipher the response the ElementTree library can be used to parse the XML. The ElementTree library is wrapped in OWSLib as etree. This part of the code example is specific to this WFS response from this service. Different WFS services will return different data. In order to examine the data the output structure must be understood. The only way to do this is to examine the returned data. Once the returned data structure is understood code can be written to perform automated queries.

In [24]:
from owslib.etree import etree

The WFS response (XML) can be parsed into an ElementTree object.

In [27]:
xmltree=etree.fromstring(wfs_response)
In [28]:
xmltree
Out[28]:
<Element {http://www.opengis.net/wfs}FeatureCollection at 0x18c88defb88>

Now we can interrogate the XML using XPath or by navigating the tree hierarchy. First, we will find the features using an XPath expression.

In [29]:
features=xmltree.findall('.//{http://www.opengis.net/gml}featureMember')
In [30]:
for feature in features:
    print (feature[0][3].text)  #[0][3] is the NAME property - found by examining the XML

        coordslist.append((float(splitpair[0]),float(splitpair[1])))

To make this plot more interesting we can view it on top of a basemap. This can be done using the matplotlib basemap module as shown below.

In [47]:
from mpl_toolkits.basemap import Basemap
In [48]:
plt.figure(figsize=(16,16))
map = Basemap(llcrnrlon=100, llcrnrlat=-50,
    urcrnrlon=160, urcrnrlat=-0,
            rsphere=(6378137.00,6356752.3142),\
            resolution='l',area_thresh=1000.,projection='lcc',\
            lat_0=-25,lon_0=130)

map.bluemarble()
map.drawstates(color='Yellow')
x1,y1=map(x,y)
plt.plot(x1,y1,color='Red')
plt.annotate('Great Barrier Reef \nWorld Heritage Area', xy=(0.75, 0.75),color='Red', size=16, xycoords='axes fraction')
plt.show()

This example has shown how to query data from a WFS and interrogate the response to extract useful information. The query to the service was straightforward but the more complex part was intepreting the data that was returned.
